title: library
new-page: true
is-special: true
go-to: menu

= The Library

This library contains reference information for the U.S. crisis scenario, including institutions, parties, blocs, and coalition mechanics.

@menu

- @government: U.S. crisis-era system of government
- @weimar_timeline: Timeline of the U.S. crisis prelude before 1932
- @curr_gov: Current government details
- @demographics: Demographics
- @parties: Parties
- @public_opinion: Public opinion (and projected election results)
- @paramilitaries: Paramilitary groups
- @factions: Internal factions
- @figures: Figures and charts
- @leaders_factions_us: Leaders and faction alignments (U.S. scenario)
- @backSpecialScene: Exit library.

@government
go-to: menu

In this scenario, the federal government is presidential, but party fragmentation has made coalition-building central to governance. The executive controls appointments and agenda-setting, while Congress determines whether legislation can actually pass.

Federal elections produce bloc strength that is translated into two legislative chambers: House and Senate. A governing arrangement needs enough House support to organize leadership (Speaker and committee control) and enough Senate support to sustain bill passage.

The President and Vice President hold the executive mandate, but reform durability depends on legislative coalition management, party conferences, and factional bargaining.

States remain politically influential through Senate composition, regional factions, and enforcement capacity.

@weimar_timeline
go-to: menu

= Timeline of the U.S. crisis prelude (until late 1932)

**1929**: Financial collapse triggers a severe depression wave. Credit contraction, business failures, and mass layoffs accelerate.

**1930**: Unemployment and social dislocation rise sharply. Traditional two-party alignment weakens as protest movements grow.

**1931**: Regional distress intensifies. Militant labor and reactionary civic formations both expand their street presence.

**1932 (early-mid)**: Presidential contest radicalizes political rhetoric. Coalition discipline deteriorates across major parties.

**1932 (late)**: The incoming administration is Democratic, but internal doctrine remains unsettled. Party conferences become decisive for strategic direction, coalition viability, and response to extremism.

